I tried this code:

```rust
#![allow(clippy::redundant_closure_call)]
#![forbid(unsafe_code)]

fn y<A, O>(f: impl Fn(&dyn Fn(A) -> O, A) -> O) -> impl Fn(A) -> O {
    trait X<A, O> {
        fn call(&self, x: &dyn X<A, O>, a: A) -> O;
    }

    impl<A, O, F> X<A, O> for F
    where
        F: Fn(&dyn X<A, O>, A) -> O,
    {
        fn call(&self, x: &dyn X<A, O>, a: A) -> O {
            (self)(x, a)
        }
    }

    move |a| {
        (|x: &dyn X<A, O>, a| (x.call(x, a)))(&|x: &dyn X<A, O>, a| (f(&|a| x.call(x, a), a)), a)
    }
}

fn fib(n: usize) -> u64 {
    let fib = y(|f, n| match n {
        0 => 0,
        1 => 1,
        2 => 1,
        n => f(n - 1) + f(n - 2),
    });
    fib(n)
}

fn main() {
    use std::io::BufRead;

    let stdin = std::io::stdin();
    let lines = stdin.lock().lines();

    for line in lines {
        let n = line.unwrap().parse::<usize>().unwrap();
        dbg!((n, fib(n)));
    }
}
```

It is an implementation of Y combinator.

I tried to compile the code but `rustc` used too much time when `opt-level=3`.

```
rustc main.rs ... (ok)
rustc main.rs -C opt-level=3 ... (timeout)
rustc +nightly main.rs -C opt-level=3 ... (timeout)
```

`rustc` generated a lot of unnecessary LLVM IR. [Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=release&edition=2018&gist=aabcde2e02ce96ce941524b34fade867)

